	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>USDA analysis of West African rice sector</h1>

			
			<h4>
												10 June 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The USDA reports a 24% increase in West African rice production in 2010/11 (excluding Nigeria and Ghana) as a result of good rains, and government and donor investment in irrigation schemes and subsidised input-supply programmes. A further increase of 10% is projected for the 2011/12 season. Rice imports are estimated at 3m tonnes, with Côte d’Ivoire and Senegal accounting for over 50% (900,000 and 700,000 tonnes respectively), around 46% of regional consumption, although Guinea Bissau, Mali and Mauritania are far less dependent on imports. Despite rapidly expanding domestic production of rice, imports are projected to remain stable given the growth in per capita rice consumption in the region. Locally produced rice is generally cheaper than imported rice, although some local rice varieties attract significant price premiums. In addition, the political crisis in Côte d’Ivoire has impacted on cross-border trade flows where Côte d’Ivoire imports bulk rice and repackages it for onward sale in the region.</p><p>The USDA report provides a detailed review for a number of countries, including a summary of how the rice trade works in each country and an analysis of the market components served by domestic and imported rice (generally urban areas prefer imported rice, while rural areas consume locally produced rice). Summary tables on rice production, consumption and trade are included for a wider range of countries including Senegal, Côte d’Ivoire, Burkina Faso, Mali, Chad, Niger, Mauritania, Gambia, Guinea Bissau, Togo and Guinea.</p><p>Rice-sector developments for Nigeria and Ghana are reviewed by USDA in separate national reviews. The analysis of the Nigerian rice sector shows increasing domestic production of rice following sustained government support for a self-sufficiency programme. This involves subsidised provision of disease-resistant rice varieties and the imposition of high import tariffs (as high as 109%, although duties of around 30% are more common). Rice millers engaged in promoting local rice production receive a tariff rebate on brown and paddy rice imports (paying only 5% in duty). High import duties have however been encouraging smuggling, mainly from Benin, and the benchmark price was reduced in January 2011 to curb the illegal trade. Nigeria nevertheless remains ‘one of the world’s largest rice importers’, importing between 1.75 and 1.95m tonnes per annum.</p><p>The USDA’s report on the grain sector in Ghana notes that the government is subsiding fertiliser prices to improve yield and actively seeking to improve the quality of local rice production. Rice consumption in Ghana is estimated at 620,000 tonnes, some 25.83 kg per capita, and rice is now a major competitor of other staple foods in Ghana.</p><p>The USDA reports note complaints of a lack of protection for the rice sector in countries such as Senegal, while the Nigerian government has placed restrictions on rice imports across land borders and the Ghanaian government applies not only the standard 20% import duty, but a range of other charges (12.5% value-added tax; 2.5% national health insurance levy; 0.5% export development and investment fund levy; 1% inspection fees; 0.5% ECOWAS levy; 0.4% Ghana customs network levy).</p><p>Rice production is also growing in Sierra Leone, with production up a third in 2009 to 784,000 tonnes, well above domestic consumption of 550,000 tonnes. This followed a major expansion of government funding for the agricultural sector, up from 1.6 to 7.7% on the way to the CAADP [Comprehensive African Agricultural Development Programme] target of 10%.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
