				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>In order to ensure that the current increases in rice production in West Africa are sustained, issues linked to improving the processing, packaging and marketing of rice now look essential. There is a wide range of experience in the region of initiatives to improve processing and packaging of locally produced rice and to address issues related to the functioning of supply chains. This suggests that benefits could be gained from the coordination of rice-sector initiatives. Such coordination could establish the basis for a regional framework for the promotion of rice production and trade, and would need to include regional agreement on quality standards for processed and packaged rice.</p><p>The reports show that varying national trade policies regarding the tariff treatment of rice in the West African region are giving rise to considerable cross-border smuggling. This is leading to the erection of barriers to trade, which does not bode well for the development of the West African regional rice trade. It also suggests the need for some increased level of policy harmonisation for rice sector initiatives in West Africa, particularly as regards the trade components of these initiatives.</p>
		</div>
		
